   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2f2794b4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Compute cost distance"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ea53b017",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Determined dis_thr"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e110a0dc",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "After identifying the LRCs, we compute the cost between any pair of points. In general, the cost is determined by the Euclidean distance; however, when LRCs and anatomical barriers are considered, the cost is redefined based on these additional constraints."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "67554727",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The parameter `dis_thr` is critical for defining how far a metabolite signal is assumed to propagate. Since the spatial scale of coordinates varies across datasets, it is important to visually inspect and adjust `dis_thr`. The function `mc.pl.plot_dis_thr` allows users to visualize this threshold by specifying the distance (`dis_thr`) and the central spot (spot_index), enabling intuitive calibration of the propagation range. Here we use `dis_thr=200`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 26,
   "id": "f7b4deb3",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "<Axes: title={'center': 'Spots within dis_thr=200 of spot 1000'}, xlabel='spatial1', ylabel='spatial2'>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 26,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 600x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "dis_thr = 200\n",
    "mc.pl.plot_dis_thr(adata = adata, dis_thr = dis_thr, spot_index = 1000)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "bb31613b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The function mc.pp.compute_costDistance() calculates the spatial cost distance matrix between all spots, integrating both Euclidean proximity and long-range channel (LRC) effects. Specifically, it adjusts the pairwise distances according to the defined `LRC_type` and their corresponding `LRC_strength`, allowing metabolite diffusion or communication along designated LRC paths to be modeled more realistically. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "196b5bfa",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The parameters `LRC_type` and `LRC_source` should correspond to the names used in adata.obs['LRC_<LRC_type>_<LRC_source>_filtered'].\n",
    "A higher value of `LRC_strength` indicates a stronger influence of long-range communication, effectively expanding the propagation range through LRCs. The parameter `dis_thr` should match the distance threshold defined in the previous step.\n",
    "We support and recommend setting `use_parallel = True` and increasing `n_jobs` within the limits of your system performance, as this can significantly accelerate the computation of the cost distance matrix. The resulting distance matrix is stored in adata.obsp (e.g., adata.obsp['spatial_distance_LRC_Blood']) and can be used in downstream analyses of metabolic cell communication."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 27,
   "id": "df8e9680",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Computing baseline spatial distance without LRC.\n",
      "  Barrier condition is not considered\n",
      "Computing spatial distance with LRCs.\n",
      "  Processing LRC type: Blood\n",
      "    Constructing graph for each LRC subcluster.\n",
      "    Computing shortest path between two points in Blood.\n",
      "      For the cluster 1 in Blood.\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "100%|██████████| 345/345 [00:00<00:00, 680.99it/s]\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "    Incorporating LRC strength of 'Blood' into cost distance matrix (strength = 5).\n",
      "adata.obsp['spatial_distance_LRC_Blood'] has been saved.\n",
      "Finished!\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "mc.pp.compute_costDistance(\n",
    "    adata = adata,\n",
    "    LRC_type = ['Blood'],\n",
    "    LRC_strength = [5],\n",
    "    LRC_source = \"marker\",\n",
    "    dis_thr = dis_thr,\n",
    "    k_neighb = 5,\n",
    "    use_parallel = True,\n",
    "    n_jobs = 64\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 28,
   "id": "781e3dd8",

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "fc1f6f17",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The function `mc.tl.metabolic_communication` performs the inference of MCC based on spatial proximity and the selected metabolite–sensor interaction database.\n",
    "Using the cost distance matrix and LRC information, it identifies potential sender–receiver pairs where metabolites can feasibly diffuse or be transported between spots within the defined distance threshold (`dis_thr`).\n",
    "In this example, 609 metabolite–sensor pairs were detected from the spatial data using the MetaChatDB reference and the Blood-related LRC configuration."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 31,
   "id": "74ebccde",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "There are 609 pairs were found from the spatial data.\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "mc.tl.metabolic_communication(adata = adata,\n",
    "                              database_name = 'MetaChatDB',\n",
    "                              df_metasen = df_metasen,\n",
    "                              LRC_type = [\"Blood\"],\n",
    "                              dis_thr = dis_thr)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b7c850ea",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "For each metabolite–sensor pair, the inferred signaling strength between all spatial spots is stored as an `n_obs × n_obs` sparse matrix in `adata.obsp['MetaChat-MetaChatDB-sender-<metabolite>-<sensor>']` and `adata.obsp['MetaChat-MetaChatDB-receiver-<metabolite>-<sensor>']`, where each entry represents the potential communication intensity from a sender spot to a receiver spot.\n",
    "Because transcriptomic (sensor) and metabolomic (metabolite) data are measured in different units, MetaChat provides two corresponding matrices — one for the `sender` (metabolite abundance) and one for the `receiver` (sensor expression).\n",
    "Their relative values are consistent, but they differ in scale to reflect the distinct quantitative units of each modality."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 32,
   "id": "b8e88df7",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "AnnData object with n_obs × n_vars = 2694 × 42069\n",
       "    obs: 'in_tissue', 'array_row', 'array_col', 'cluster_miso', 'highlight', 'tissue_type', 'LRC_Blood_marker_MYH11', 'LRC_Blood_marker_CLDN5', 'LRC_Blood_avg_markers', 'LRC_Blood_marker_unfiltered', 'LRC_Blood_marker_filtered', 'LRC_Blood_closepoint_cluster1'\n",

   "source": [
    "The matrices `adata.obsm['MetaChat–MetaChatDB–sum–sender']` and `adata.obsm['MetaChat–MetaChatDB–sum–receiver']` represent the total communication strength of each spot acting as a sender or receiver, respectively.\n",
    "Technically, these values are obtained by summing the corresponding rows (for senders) and columns (for receivers) of each metabolite–sensor communication matrix, providing a global measure of how actively each spot participates in metabolite-mediated signaling."
   ]
